V{{Infobox philosopher\u000a|region           = Western Philosophy\u000a|era              = [[20th-century philosophy]]\u000a|name             = Christine Marion Korsgaard\u000a|image            = Christine Korsgaard at Amherst College 2.jpg\u000a|image_size = 200px\u000a|birth_date       = April 9, 1952 (age 64)\u000a|birth_place      = [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States]]\u000a|alma_mater       = [[Harvard University]]\u000a|school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy|Analytic]]\u000a|institutions     = [[Harvard University]]\u000a|main_interests   = [[Ethics|Moral philosophy]]{{·}} [[Kantianism]]\u000a|influences       = [[Immanuel Kant]] {{·}} [[John Rawls]]\u000a|influenced       = [[Austin Dacey]] {{·}} [[Derek Parfit]]\u000a|notable_ideas    =\u000a}}\u000a'''Christine Marion Korsgaard''' (born April 9, 1952) is an [[United States|American]] [[philosopher]] and academic whose main scholarly interests are in [[Ethics|moral philosophy]] and its history; the relation of issues in moral philosophy to issues in [[metaphysics]], the [[philosophy of mind]], and the theory of [[personal identity]]; the theory of [[personal relationship]]s; and in [[Norm (sociology)|normativity]] in general. She has taught at [[Yale University|Yale]], the [[University of California at Santa Barbara]], and the [[University of Chicago]]; since 1991 she has been a professor at [[Harvard University]], where she is now Arthur Kingsley Porter Professor of Philosophy.  She has been described as "one of today's leading moral philosophers"<ref>https://ndpr.nd.edu/news/24047-the-constitution-of-agency-essays-on-practical-reason-and-moral-psychology/</ref> because of her work in defense of [[Kantian ethics|Kantian views in moral theory]].\u000a\u000a==Biography==\u000aKorsgaard first attended Eastern Illinois University for two years and transferred to receive a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]] from Harvard, where she was a student of [[John Rawls]]. She received an LHD [[Doctor of Humane Letters]] from the [[University of Illinois]] in 2004.<ref>http://commencement.illinois.edu/ceremonies/honors_awards.html</ref> She is a 1970 alumna of [[Homewood-Flossmoor High School]] in Flossmoor, Ill.\u000a\u000aIn 1996 Korsgaard published a book entitled ''The Sources of Normativity'', which was the revised version of her [[Tanner Lectures on Human Values]], and also a collection of her past papers on [[Immanuel Kant|Kant]]'s moral philosophy and Kantian approaches to contemporary moral philosophy: ''Creating the Kingdom of Ends''. In 2002, she was the first woman to give the [[John Locke Lectures]] at the [[University of Oxford]],<ref>http://www.philosophy.ox.ac.uk/lectures/john_locke_lectures/past_lectures</ref> which turned into her most recent book, ''Self-Constitution: Agency, Identity, and Integrity''.\u000a\u000aShe was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts & Sciences]] in 2001<ref>http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/2001/05.24/07-academy.html</ref> and a Corresponding Fellow of the [[British Academy]] in 2015.<ref>http://www.britac.ac.uk/fellowship/elections/index.cfm?year=2015</ref>\u000a\u000a==Selected publications==\u000a===Books===\u000a* (2009) ''[[Self-Constitution]]: Agency, Identity, and Integrity'', Oxford University Press.\u000a* (2008) ''The Constitution of Agency'', Oxford University Press.\u000a* (1996a) ''The Sources of Normativity'', New York: Cambridge University Press, ISBN 0-521-55059-9.\u000a* (1996b) ''Creating the Kingdom of Ends'', New York: Cambridge University Press, ISBN 0-521-49644-6.\u000a\u000a===Articles===\u000a* (1986) "Skepticism about Practical Reason," ''The Journal of Philosophy'' 83 (1): 5-25.  (Reprinted in as ch.11 in Korsgaard (1996b), pp.&nbsp;311\u2013334.)\u000a* (1997) "The Normativity of Instrumental Reason", ch. 8 in Garrett Cullity & Berys Gaut (eds.) ''Ethics and Practical Reason'', Oxford: Clarendon Press, pp.&nbsp;215\u201354.  (Reprinted with Afterword in Korsgaard (2008), pp.&nbsp;27\u201369.)\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a*[[American philosophy]]\u000a*[[List of American philosophers]]\u000a\u000a==Notes==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a*[http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~korsgaar/ Korsgaard's Web Page] - at Harvard University.\u000a*[http://www.3ammagazine.com/3am/treating-people-as-ends-in-themselves/ Interview with 3AM Magazine]\u000a\u000a{{Ethics}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Korsgaard, Christine}}\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:American women philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:1952 births]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\u000a[[Category:Kantian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Deontological ethics]]\u000a[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Analytic philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American people of Danish descent]]\u000a[[Category:Moral philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:American ethicists]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of mind]]
